---
import MaxLoanCalculator from "@/components/calculators/MaxLoanCalculator";
import ToolShell from "@/components/dscr/ToolShell.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is a multifamily loan sizing calculator?",
    a: "A loan sizing calculator estimates maximum proceeds by testing DSCR, debt yield, and LTV constraints together. The binding constraint—the lowest proceeds amount—usually drives the lender term sheet.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do lenders size multifamily loans?",
    a: "Lenders calculate max loan from each metric (DSCR floor, debt yield floor, LTV cap) and lend to the lowest result. Sponsors should model base and downside cases before selecting a product.",
  },
  {
    q: "Which constraint binds most often?",
    a: "It depends on market, rate environment, and asset stage. In tight spread environments, debt yield often binds on stabilized deals. Value-add bridge deals may bind on in-place DSCR or LTV until stabilization.",
  },
  {
    q: "Should I size to maximum leverage?",
    a: "Not always. Maximum proceeds reduce equity requirement but shrink covenant headroom. Many experienced sponsors target conservative sizing to preserve refinance optionality.",
  },
  {
    q: "How does property value affect loan sizing?",
    a: "LTV caps proceeds as a percentage of appraised or lender value. NOI drives DSCR and debt yield caps. Weak value opinions or thin NOI can bind before leverage targets are reached.",
  },
  {
    q: "Can I use this for agency and bridge scenarios?",
    a: "Yes. Change DSCR, debt yield, and LTV assumptions to match each product's typical underwriting band, then compare proceeds side by side before requesting quotes.",
  },
];
---

<ToolShell
  title="Multifamily Loan Calculator | Multi-Family USA"
  description="Free multifamily loan sizing calculator. Find max proceeds from DSCR, debt yield, and LTV constraints with formulas and a worked 5+ unit example."
  h1="Multifamily Loan Sizing Calculator"
  toolSlug="loan-sizing-calculator"
  tagline="Back into maximum supportable debt from DSCR, debt yield, and LTV—the three metrics that bind most apartment loan term sheets."
  keywords={["multifamily loan calculator", "loan sizing calculator", "apartment loan proceeds", "ltv dscr debt yield", "commercial multifamily"]}
  relatedGuides={["multifamily-underwriting-basics", "debt-yield-and-ltv-framework", "capital-stack-design-for-value-add"]}
  relatedComparisons={["fixed-vs-floating-rate", "agency-vs-bridge"]}
  relatedLoanTypes={["agency-stabilized", "bank-balance-sheet", "bridge-value-add"]}
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <Fragment slot="calculator">
    <MaxLoanCalculator client:load />
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none dark:prose-invert">
      <h2>How to size a multifamily loan</h2>
      <p>
        Commercial multifamily proceeds are usually limited by the lowest of three calculations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>DSCR constraint:</strong> Max Debt Service = NOI ÷ Min DSCR → solve for loan from payment</li>
        <li><strong>Debt yield constraint:</strong> Max Loan = NOI ÷ Min Debt Yield</li>
        <li><strong>LTV constraint:</strong> Max Loan = Property Value × Max LTV</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The binding constraint determines proceeds. Always stress NOI and rates in downside cases.</p>

      <h2>Worked example: 56-unit stabilized acquisition</h2>
      <p>
        NOI: <strong>$980,000</strong>. Value: <strong>$14,000,000</strong>. Lender floors: 1.25x DSCR, 9.25% debt yield, 75% LTV. At a 6.5% rate and 30-year amortization, annual debt service on a $10.5M loan ≈ $798,000.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>DSCR max ≈ $10.5M (1.23x at that balance—near floor)</li>
        <li>Debt yield max: $980,000 ÷ 0.0925 ≈ <strong>$10.59M</strong></li>
        <li>LTV max: $14M × 75% = <strong>$10.5M</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Proceeds likely bind near <strong>$10.5M</strong>. Explore structure trade-offs in our <a href="/learn/agency-vs-bridge-execution">agency vs bridge execution guide</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>
</ToolShell>
